I want to write a series of articles about front-end knowledge needed for interviews. At first, I just made a few notes for myself, but I realized it might be worth sharing them. This article explains how JavaScript runs in the browser, what best practices look like, and what JavaScript actually is in reality.
Interview questions shouldn’t be learned or taken in isolation. Instead, you should learn the underlying concepts first to really understand what you are programming. How Javascript Runs In The Browser — Event Loop
Press enter or click to view image in full size

My Event Loop ChartI suggest learning this concept in a way that allows you to explain it to someone else, as this is the core of JavaScript.
Let’s start with the Call Stack
It is the beating heart of JavaScript engines, and this is how your code is read in the browser.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

If you are not familiar with stacks, you can check this out: https://dev.to/bekbrace/stack-and-queue-34de . Basically, you can view a stack as an array in LIFO (Last In, First Out) order where you push and pop items.
But Wait a Minute, Does This Mean JavaScript Has to Wait for a BE Response and Block Everything?
Press enter or click to view image in full size

A minute to think about, credit to: https://www.pexels.com/@mikhail-nilov/Of course not — things are a bit more complex. Let’s think about performance for a moment. Imagine you need to process a large amount of data, perform calculations on the client, and then call a few APIs in sequence. What happens?
Easiest Part: Web API(s): https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API
If you call an API using fetch(), for example, you delegate that instruction to the browser. The browser performs some "magic" over the network and receives the response. Then, it delegates the callback to the Microtask queue, which eventually pushes it onto the Call Stack. Meanwhile, the stack remains unblocked, and the user can keep using your wonderful app.
YAY.
But hey, what is the difference between the Microtask Queue and the Task Queue?
Easy! Did you forget about setTimeout()? If you call setTimeout(), its callback goes directly to the Task Queue (Macrotask Queue):
function triggerBothQueues() {
console.log("1. Synchronous: Code starts on Call Stack"); // Enqueue a Macrotask (Task Queue)
setTimeout(() => {
console.log("4. Task Queue (Macrotask): setTimeout callback executed");
}, 0);
// Enqueue a Microtask (Microtask Queue)
Promise.resolve().then(() => {
console.log("3. Microtask Queue: Promise.then callback executed");
});
console.log("2. Synchronous: Code ends on Call Stack");
}
triggerBothQueues();
Output:

• Synchronous: Code starts on Call Stack

• Synchronous: Code ends on Call Stack

• Microtask Queue: Promise.then callback executed

• Task Queue (Macrotask): setTimeout callback executed
But I Heard About the Heap or Something…?
Hell yeah: The Heap is JavaScript’s dedicated storage for Objects, Arrays, and anything stored by reference. On the other hand, primitive types (booleans, numbers) local to function execution are handled directly via execution context on the Call Stack. (Well, it’s not quite that simple — large strings use a string pool inside the heap, and primitives inside objects live on the heap too, but let’s not overcomplicate things right now haha :D).
So How Do We Get Values Out of the Heap… Or Is It Infinite Storage?
Nooooo, it is not infinite! Have you heard about…
The Garbage Collector?
A garbage collector is a background engine process that cleans up unused memory in the heap.
How It Works: Reachability
JavaScript determines which memory to keep or release based on the concept of Reachability.

• Roots: A core set of inherently reachable values (e.g., global variables, active function parameters, and local variables on the Call Stack).

• Reachable Values: Any object or value accessible by following a chain of references starting from a Root.
If an object in the Heap can no longer be reached from any Root, it is considered “garbage” and collected.
Here is how you can accidentally create a memory leak:
function startDashboardTracker() {
const hugeDataPayload = new Array(1000000).fill("data"); // Timer is launched
setInterval(() => {
// Because hugeDataPayload is referenced here,
// it stays trapped in memory forever!
console.log("Tracker pinging... Payload length:", hugeDataPayload.length);
}, 1000);
}
startDashboardTracker();
// Even after startDashboardTracker finishes executing and leaves the Call Stack,
// hugeDataPayload CANNOT be garbage collected because the timer's closure holds a reference to it.
The Fix
Store the timer ID and call clearInterval() when the operation completes or when a UI component unmounts.
function setupSearchWidget() {
// Heavy data tied to the widget scope
const heavySearchIndex = new Array(1000000).fill("search_index_item"); function handleResize() {
console.log("Window resized. Index size:", heavySearchIndex.length);
}
// Listener attached to the global 'window' object (a Root)
window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);
}
setupSearchWidget();
// Later, user navigates away and the Search Widget DOM element is deleted.
// BUT 'window' still holds a reference to 'handleResize',
// which holds a reference to 'heavySearchIndex'.
The Fix
Explicitly detach event listeners using removeEventListener when an element or page section is destroyed.
Let’s think about this for a moment… Why do frameworks like React and Angular make event handling easier? Under the hood, they use Event Delegation. Instead of attaching individual event listeners to every single DOM node (which wastes memory), React listens for events as they bubble up to the root container and dispatches them automatically. Plus, synthetic event systems automatically attach and detach handlers as components mount and unmount.
What Is Event Bubbling
