Screenshot from above codeThis code snippet comes from a talk I gave at CodeCon. Here we can see how event bubbling works in practice, along with a performance “hack.”
The performance advantage is that by placing a single event listener on a top-level parent div, you can listen for events on all nested children while saving memory—which is similar to what modern frameworks do under the hood.
At the same time, you can stop propagation using stopPropagation(): https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Event/stopPropagation
I recommend experimenting with event bubbling directly. It feels odd to write Angular or React code without knowing how to attach a solid vanilla addEventListener in raw JS!
What Exactly Is Functional Programming?
Think of Functional Programming (FP) as an assembly line where data moves through a series of completely isolated machines (functions). Each machine receives raw materials, produces a result, and leaves everything else untouched.
Unlike Object-Oriented Programming—where objects constantly mutate internal state—FP avoids mutating data. Instead, it relies on five core principles:

• Pure Functions: Predictable code that relies exclusively on its inputs and never side-effects external state.

• Immutability: Data is persistent; transformations return new copies rather than modifying the original object.

• First-Class Functions: Treats logic like data—you can pass functions into other functions or assign them to variables.

• Higher-Order Functions: Functions that accept other functions as arguments or return them to build modular code: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/javascript/javascript-higher-order-functions/

• Declarative Logic: You describe what computation to achieve rather than manually managing loop counters and state changes.
Classes — OOP In Javascript
// 1. PURE JAVASCRIPT (Native ES2022+)
class BankAccount {
#balance = 0; // Native JS private field (using #) constructor(owner, initialBalance) {
this.owner = owner;
this.#balance = initialBalance;
}
deposit(amount) {
this.#balance += amount;
}
}
const account = new BankAccount("Alex", 1000);
// account.#balance; ❌ Uncaught SyntaxError (Hard runtime privacy)
JavaScript utilizes Prototypal Inheritance under the hood. I won’t dive too deeply into this topic here as it gets complex quickly (before ES6 classes, developers emulated classes using constructor functions). Furthermore, modern front-end development heavily favors “composition over inheritance.”
Here is how OOP patterns looked before ES6:
// 1. BASE CONSTRUCTOR FUNCTION (Parent Class)
function BankAccount(owner, initialBalance) {
this.owner = owner; // Public property // PRIVATE VARIABLE (Data Privacy via Closure)
// Lives in function scope, completely hidden from the outside world!
var balance = initialBalance;
// Public method privileged to access the private 'balance' variable
this.deposit = function (amount) {
balance += amount;
this._logTransaction("Deposited $" + amount + ". New Balance: $" + balance);
};
}
// PROTECTED / SHARED METHODS (Prototypal Inheritance)
// Attached to the prototype so methods aren't re-created for every single instance
BankAccount.prototype._logTransaction = function (action) {
console.log("[" + this.owner + "]: " + action);
};
// 2. DERIVED CONSTRUCTOR FUNCTION (Child Class)
function SavingsAccount(owner, initialBalance, interestRate) {
// Call Parent Constructor with 'this' context (Super Call)
BankAccount.call(this, owner, initialBalance);
this.interestRate = interestRate;
}
// Inherit parent prototype methods on the child
SavingsAccount.prototype = Object.create(BankAccount.prototype);
SavingsAccount.prototype.constructor = SavingsAccount; // Reset constructor reference
// Child Public Method
SavingsAccount.prototype.addInterest = function () {
// Calls the inherited prototype method
this._logTransaction("Applied " + this.interestRate + "% interest");
};
// 3. USAGE
var mySavings = new SavingsAccount("Alex", 1000, 5);
mySavings.deposit(200); // -> [Alex]: Deposited $200. New Balance: $1200
mySavings.addInterest(); // -> [Alex]: Applied 5% interest
If you need a real OOP principles, it is better to use Typescript, but I recommend to go through this nice detailed OOP in javascript: https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/javascript/introduction-object-oriented-programming-javascript/
What else?
JavaScript is vast! Beyond these basics, you can explore the HTML5 Canvas API, Browser Web APIs, JS Modules, Iterators, Generators, and Closures — which we’ll look at next.
Closures
Simply put, a closure occurs when a function is bundled together with its surrounding lexical environment. Or as an English Lord might say:
